= section "Introduction to kəthēb Verbs" do
  %p <i>Kəthēb</i> (Active Scale II) is commonly known as the “intensive” or “transitive” stem. In other Semitic languages it is responsible for a large variety of meanings, ranging from a strengthening of the action (the intensive proper) to an iterative, declarative, or causative. In Alashian, however, it has a much more restricted usage: it creates the base form of quadriconsonantal roots (which cannot conjugate in <i>katab</i>), and it forms transitive verbs from stative (adjectival) roots, typically with a causative or inceptive meaning. Examples of the former include #{t "καλκήλ", "kalkēl"} “ring”, #{t "βαλβήλ", "balbēl"} “confuse”, and #{t "ταργήν", "targēn"} “translate”, while the latter group includes #{t "λαττήφ", "ləthēf"} “shrink, reduce, make small” (*lthīf “be small”), #{t "в̄ασσήν", "vəssēn"} “put [a child] to sleep, say good night” (*wsīn “sleep”), and #{t "в̄ακκήδ", "vəkhēd"} “set alight” (*wkhād “burn”).
  %p Very occasionally a root with a transitive meaning in <i>katab</i> may also have a <i>kəthēb</i> counterpart. These are by and large relic forms and this is not a productive process. The meaning tends to be broadly causative, but generally with a more specific nuance of urging action rather than simply causing it. For instance, the root *dkīr “remember”, which has the Scale I form #{t "δάκαρ", "dakar"} “remember”, becomes #{t "δακκήρ", "dəkhēr"} “exhort, remind of the consequences of doing/not doing” (in contrast to the true Scale III causative #{t "αδ̄κήρ", "'aḏkēr"} “remind [of a fact]”).
  %p The most distinctive feature is the gemination or aspiration of the #{template "C2"} consonant or, in the case of quadriconsonantal roots, the reinterpretation of this #{template "C1VC2C2VC3-"} pattern as #{template "-C1VC2C3VC4-"}, with the gemination replaced by two root consonants. It is this structure that gives this conjugation the name “D-Stem” (for “doubled”) in comparative Semitic literature.

= section "Triconsonantal Roots and kəthēb" do
  = section "The Present Tense" do
    %p The present tense is formed by adding the standard set of prefixes and suffixes to the <i>kəthēb</i> present tense stem. For most roots, the stem takes the form #{template "*-C1əC2C2aC3-"} with a geminate medial consonant when there is no suffix, and as a contracted #{template "*-C1əC2C3-"} where there is a suffix. If #{template "C2"} is one of *P/T/K/Č, it will become a non-geminated aspirate in the former case.
    %p Unlike in <i>katab</i>, there is no trace of the inherent root vowel in the <i>kəthēb</i> present tense. As a result, Barth's Law does not apply, and the prefix vowel is always /i/ (except in the first person singular, where it is /a/).
    %p The roots *sdīr “be ready” and *dkīr “remember” may be used to demonstrate the regular conjugation of <i>kəthēb</i>, where they take the forms #{t "σαδδήρ", "səddēr"} “prepare, make ready” and #{t "δακκήρ", "dəkhēr"} “exhort, remind”:
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(άσαδδαρ τίσαδδαρ τισαδρεί ίσαδδαρ ισαδρεί νισαδρού τισαδρού τισαδρού ισαδρού ισαδρού)
        - latin = %w('asəddar tisəddar tisədrī yisəddar yisədrī nisədrū tisədrū tisədrū yisədrū yisədrū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "səddēr", :eng => "prepare" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(άδακκαρ τίδακκαρ τιδακρεί ίδακκαρ ιδακρεί νιδακρού τιδακρού τιδακρού ιδακρού ιδακρού)
        - latin = %w('adəkhar tidəkhar tidəkrī yidəkhar yidəkrī nidəkrū tidəkrū tidəkrū yidəkrū yidəkrū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "dəkhēr", :eng => "exhort" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Preterite Tense" do
    %p The preterite tense is formed by adding regular preterite endings to the stem #{template "*C1əC2C2ēC3-"}, replacing the gemination with aspiration if appropriate. In the third person singular feminine and third person plural, the schwa will become /i/ so long as #{template "C2"} does not surface as an aspirate.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(σαδδήρετ σαδδήρτα σαδδήρσ̄ε σαδδήρ σιδδηρώ σαδδηρνώ σαδδήρτυν σαδδήρσ̄ιν σιδδηρού σιδδηρού)
        - latin = %w(səddēret səddērta səddērše səddēr siddērā səddērnā səddērtun səddēršin siddērū siddērū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "səddēr", :eng => "prepare" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(δακκήρετ δακκήρτα δακκήρσ̄ε δακκήρ δακκηρώ δακκηρνώ δακκήρτυν δακκήρσ̄ιν δακκηρού δακκηρού)
        - latin = %w(dəkhēret dəkhērta dəkhērše dəkhēr dəkhērā dəkhērnā dəkhērtun dəkhēršin dəkhērū dəkhērū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "dəkhēr", :eng => "exhort" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperfect Tense" do
    %p The imperfect tense is formed by adding regular endings to the stem #{template "*C1eC2C2eC3-"}, or #{template "*C1əC2eC3-"} if #{template "C2"} surfaces as an aspirate (note the difference in vowel quality). If #{template "C3"} can undergo lenition, it does so in all of the first and second person forms. Unlike in <i>katab</i>, there is never any stem contraction.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(σέδδερ σέδδερετ σέδδερες̄ σέδδερ σεδδερώ σέδδερεν σέδδερτυν σέδδερσ̄ιν σεδδερού σεδδερού)
        - latin = %w(sedder sedderet seddereš sedder sedderā sedderen seddertun sedderšin sedderū sedderū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "səddēr", :eng => "prepare" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(δάκκερ δάκκερετ δάκκερες̄ δάκκερ δακκερώ δάκκερεν δάκκερτυν δάκκερσ̄ιν δακκερού δακκερού)
        - latin = %w(dəkher dəkheret dəkhereš dəkher dəkherā dəkheren dəkhertun dəkheršin dəkherū dəkherū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "dəkhēr", :eng => "exhort" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Perfective Subjunctive Tense" do
    %p The <i>kəthēb</i> perfective subjunctive is formed by adding a special set of prefixes to the stem #{template "*-C1əC2C2eC3"}, or #{template "*-C1əC2eC3"} if #{template "C2"} is an aspirate. While the prefixes share a strong resemblence to those of <i>katab</i>, the vowels and stress patterns are different.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(в̄άσαδδερ в̄ετείσαδδερ в̄ήσαδδερ в̄ενείσαδδερ в̄ετείσαδδερ в̄ήσαδδερ)
        - latin = %w(vasədder vetīsədder vēsədder venīsədder vetīsədder vēsədder)
        %td= render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale II Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "səddēr", :eng => "prepare" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(в̄άδακκερ в̄ετείδακκερ в̄ήδακκερ в̄ενείδακκερ в̄ετείδακκερ в̄ήδακκερ)
        - latin = %w(vadəkher vetīdəkher vēdəkher venīdəkher vetīdəkher vēdəkher)
        %td= render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale II Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "dəkhēr", :eng => "exhort" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Imperative" do
    %p The masculine singular takes the form #{template "*C1əC2C2ēC3"}/#{template "*C1əC2ēC3"}, while the feminine singular and plural forms add the normal imperative endings to the contracted stem #{template "*C1əC2C2eC3-"}/#{template "*C1əC2eC3-"}.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(σαδδήρ σαδδερεί σαδδερού σαδδερού)
        - latin = %w(səddēr sədderī sədderū sədderū)
        %td= render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale II Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "səddēr", :eng => "prepare" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(δακκήρ δακκερεί δακκερού δακκερού)
        - latin = %w(dəkhēr dəkherī dəkherū dəkherū)
        %td= render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale II Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "dəkhēr", :eng => "exhort" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "Deverbatives" do
    %p <i>Kəthēb</i> has only two deverbatives: an infinitive and an active participle. The infinitive uses the pattern #{template "*maC1əC2C2ūC3"}, while the participle uses #{template "*muC1əC2C2iC3"}, replacing gemination with aspiration when appropriate.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μασαδδούρ", :lat => "masəddūr", :meaning => "prepare" },
                       { :name => "Active Part.", :ala => "μύσαδδιρ", :lat => "musəddir", :meaning => "preparing" } ]
        %td= render 'deverbative_table', :title => "Scale II Deverbatives", :verb => { :ala => "səddēr", :eng => "prepare" }, :forms => alashian
        - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μαδακκούρ", :lat => "madəkhūr", :meaning => "exhort" },
                       { :name => "Active Part.", :ala => "μύδακκιρ", :lat => "mudəkhir", :meaning => "exhorting" } ]
        %td= render 'deverbative_table', :title => "Scale II Deverbatives", :verb => { :ala => "dəkhēr", :eng => "exhort" }, :forms => alashian

= section "Biconsonantal Roots and kəthēb" do
  %p Biconsonantal roots may be conjugated in <i>kəthēb</i>, but only by first converting them to standard triconsonantal roots via internal extension (the addition of #{template "C2"} *W for roots with *ū, *Y for roots with *ī or *ē, and *' for roots with *ā). These then conjugate as though they were triconsonantal verbs in all forms.
  %p Two examples are the roots *čīl “cold” and *řūn “hot”, which in <i>kəthēb</i> yield the verbs #{t "τζαιιήλ", "čəyyēl"} “cool, make cold” and #{t "ρ̄αυυήν", "řəwwēn"} “heat, make hot”. Their conjugation is essentially as though they were always triconsonantal, with the addition of an epenthetic vowel /a/ in some present tense forms to prevent an illegal cluster: #{t "τιτζαιαλεί", "tičəyalī"} “you (f) are cooling” (not **tičəylī), #{t "νερ̄αυανού", "neřəwanū"} “we are heating” (not **neřəwnū)#{footnote}.
  - alashian = { :present     => %w(άτζαιιαλ τίτζαιιαλ τιτζαιαλεί ίτζαιιαλ ιτζαιαλεί νιτζαιαλού τιτζαιαλού τιτζαιαλού ιτζαιαλού),
                 :preterite   => %w(τζαιιήλετ τζαιιήλτα τζαιιήλσ̄ε τζαιιήλ τζιιηλώ τζαιιηλνώ τζαιιήλτυν τζαιιήλσ̄ιν τζιιηλού),
                 :imperfect   => %w(τζέιιελ τζέιιελετ τζέιιελες̄ τζέιιελ τζειιελώ τζέιιελεν τζέιιελτυν τζέιιελσ̄ιν τζειιελού),
                 :subjunctive => %w(в̄άτζαιιελ в̄ετείτζαιιελ в̄ετείτζαιιελ в̄ήτζαιιελ в̄ήτζαιιελ в̄ενείτζαιιελ в̄ετείτζαιιελ в̄ετείτζαιιελ в̄ήτζαιιελ),
                 :imperative  => %w(τζαιιήλ τζαιιελεί τζαιιελού),
                 :infinitive  => "ματζαιιούλ",
                 :participle  => "μύτζαιιλ" }
  - latin = { :present     => %w('ačəyyal tičəyyal tičəyalī yičəyyal yičəyalī ničəyalū tičəyalū tičəyalū yičəyalū),
              :preterite   => %w(čəyyēlet čəyyēlta čəyyēlše čəyyēl čiyyēlā čəyyēlnā čəyyēltun čəyyēlšin čiyyēlū),
              :imperfect   => %w(čeyyel čeyyelet čeyyeleš čeyyel čeyyelā čeyyelen čeyyeltun čeyyelšin čeyyelū),
              :subjunctive => %w(vačəyyel vetīčəyyel vetīčəyyel vēčəyyel vēčəyyel venīčəyyel vetīčəyyel vetīčəyyel vēčəyyel),
              :imperative  => %w(čəyyēl čəyyelī čəyyelū),
              :infinitive  => "mačəyyūl",
              :participle  => "mučəyyil" }
  = render 'full_conjugation_table', :title => "Scale II Conjugation", :verb => { :ala => "čəyyēl", :eng => "cool" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

= section "Quadriconsonantal Roots and kəthēb" do
  %p Quadriconsonantal roots are the most common verbs that use the <i>kəthēb</i> pattern. Their conjugation requires only a few slight modifications to the triconsonantal paradigm:
  %ul
    %li The #{template "C2C2"} gemination of triconsonantal roots is replaced everywhere with two single consonants, #{template "C2C3"}.
    %li The schwa is replaced everywhere with /a/.
    %li An epenthetic /a/ is present in suffixed present tense forms to prevent the formation of illegal clusters.
  %p With #{t "ταργήν", "targēn"} “translate”:
  - alashian = { :present     => %w(άταργαν τίταργαν τιταργανεί ίταργαν ιταργανεί νιταργανού τιταργανού τιταργανού ιταργανού),
                 :preterite   => %w(ταργήνετ ταργήντα ταργήνσ̄ε ταργήν τιργηνώ ταργηννώ ταργήντυν ταργήνσ̄ιν τιργηνού),
                 :imperfect   => %w(τέργεν τέργενετ τέργενες̄ τεργήν τεργενώ τέργενεν τέργεντυν τέργενσ̄ιν τεργενού),
                 :subjunctive => %w(в̄άταργεν в̄ετείταργεν в̄ετείταργεν в̄ήταργεν в̄ήταργεν в̄ενείταργεν в̄ετείταργεν в̄ετείταργεν в̄ήταργεν),
                 :imperative  => %w(ταργήν ταργενεί ταργενού),
                 :infinitive  => "ματαργούν",
                 :participle  => "μύταργιν" }
  - latin = { :present     => %w('atargan titargan titarganī yitargan yitarganī nitarganū titarganū titarganū yitarganū),
              :preterite   => %w(targēnet targēnta targēnše targēn tirgēnā targēnnā targēntun targēnšin tirgēnū),
              :imperfect   => %w(tergen tergenet tergeneš tergēn tergenā tergenen tergentun tergenšin tergenū),
              :subjunctive => %w(vatargen vetītargen vetītargen vētargen vētargen venītargen vetītargen vetītargen vētargen),
              :imperative  => %w(targēn targenī targenū),
              :infinitive  => "matargūn",
              :participle  => "mutargin" }
  = render 'full_conjugation_table', :title => "Scale II Conjugation", :verb => { :ala => "targēn", :eng => "translate" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

