= section "Introduction to kəthāb Verbs" do
  %p <i>Kəthāb</i>, or Passive Scale II, is the passive counterpart to <i>kəthēb</i>. It is derived from <i>kəthēb</i> via the internal passive vowel pattern -u-ā-, while maintaining the distinctive gemination of <i>kəthēb</i>. However, some modifications have been made to certain forms due to the merger of short vowels before aspirates in order to maintain the saliency of passive marking.
  %p Any transitive <i>kəthēb</i> verb may be made passive by shifting it to <i>kəthāb</i>: #{t "τυργών", "turgān"} “be translated”, #{t "λαττώφ", "ləthāf"} “be shrunk”, #{t "в̄ακκώδ", "vəkhād"} “be set alight”, #{t "σαδδώρ", "səddār"} “be prepared”.

= section "Triconsonantal Roots and kəthāb" do
  = section "The Present Tense" do
    %p The present tense is formed by adding the present tense prefixes and suffixes to the stems #{template "*-C1əC2C2āC3-"} (when there is no suffix) or #{template "*-C1əC2C2aC3-"} (when there is a suffix), replacing the geminates with aspirates if appropriate. The schwa is these forms was once /u/ (from the -u-ā- passive vowel pattern), but was centralized to /ə/ before aspirated consonants and subsequently generalized.
    %p As a result, <i>kəthāb</i> forms came to look very similar to their active voice <i>kəthēb</i> counterparts. This was resolved by reintroducing -u- as the <em>prefix vowel</em>: first person plural *nu-, second person *tu-, third person *yu-. Even the first person singular marker became *'u-, making <i>kəthāb</i> the only conjugation to mark the first person singular present with a vowel other than /a/ or /aː/.
    %p The verbs used below are #{t "σαδδώρ", "səddār"} “be prepared”, the passive of #{t "σαδδήρ", "səddēr"} “prepare”, and #{t "δακκώρ", "dəkhār"} “be brought to [someone's] mind”, the passive of #{t "δακκήρ", "dəkhēr"} “remind [someone of the consequences of an action]”.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(υσαδδώρ τυσαδδώρ τυσαδδαρεί ιυσαδδώρ ιυσαδδαρεί νυσαδδαρού τυσαδδαρού τυσαδδαρού ιυσαδδαρού ιυσαδδαρού)
        - latin = %w('usəddār tusəddār tusəddarī yusəddār yusəddarī nusəddarū tusəddarū tusəddarū yusəddarū yusəddarū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "səddār", :eng => "be prepared" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(υδακκώρ τυδακκώρ τυδακκαρεί ιυδακκώρ ιυδακκαρεί νυδακκαρού τυδακκαρού τυδακκαρού ιυδακκαρού ιυδακκαρού)
        - latin = %w('udəkhār tudəkhār tudəkharī yudəkhār yudəkharī nudəkharū tudəkharū tudəkharū yudəkharū yudəkharū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "dəkhār", :eng => "be brought to mind" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "The Preterite Tense" do
    %p The preterite is formed by adding the usual preterite endings to the stem #{template "*C1əC2C2āC3-"}. The conjugation is thus essentially the same as <i>kəthēb</i>, except for the vowel /aː/ in place of the <i>kəthēb</i> /eː/. There is no /ə/~/i/ alternation in the third person as seen in <i>kəthēb</i>.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(σαδδώρετ σαδδώρτα σαδδώρσ̄ε σαδδώρ σαδδωρώ σαδδωρνώ σαδδώρτυν σαδδώρσ̄ιν σαδδωρού σαδδωρού)
        - latin = %w(səddāret səddārta səddārše səddār səddārā səddārnā səddārtun səddāršin səddārū səddārū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "səddār", :eng => "be prepared" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
        - alashian = %w(δακκώρετ δακκώρτα δακκώρσ̄ε δακκώρ δακκωρώ δακκωρνώ δακκώρτυν δακκώρσ̄ιν δακκωρού δακκωρού)
