= section "Weak Roots in Scale II" do
  %p <i>Kəthēb</i> and <i>kəthāb</i> are for the most part much more regular than <i>katab</i> and <i>nuktāb</i>, though there are still a number of irregular subclasses.

  = section "C1 = Ř" do
    %p Roots with initial root consonant *Ř are completely regular except in the present tense of active <i>kəthēb</i>. Here, the prefix vowel /i/ is lowered to /e/ throughout. For example, the root *řdāṯ “new, recent” produces the verb <i>řəddēṯ</i> “renew, restore” with the third person singular masculine present #{t "ιέρ̄αδδαθ", "yeřəddaṯ"} “he is renewing/restoring” (not **yiřəddaṯ).

  = section "C2 = Ř" do
    %p Roots with medial *Ř cause some problems in Scale II because the geminated **řř is not permitted in Alashian. Two different methods have arisen to resolve this.
    %p Historically, this was fixed by having the vowel immediately before the *Ř lengthen in compensation for the lack of gemination. Alashian, however, has no long schwa, so the vowel that would be inserted was the long version of whatever the original vowel had once been. For instance, the root *lřāb “wide, spacious” produced the verbs #{t "λωρ̄ήβ", "lāřēb"} “widen, expand” (not **ləřřēb) and #{t "λουρ̄ώβ", "lūřāb"} “be widened, expanded” (not **ləřřāb). This technique is the only one seen in texts from the 19th century and earlier.
    %p However, this method required the reintroduction of vowels whose quality had been lost in other triconsonantal verbs for centuries. As a result, over time many speakers generalized the schwa seen in the rest of triconsonantal Scale II while preserving the non-gemination of *Ř, giving the forms #{t "λαρ̄ήβ", "ləřēb"} “widen, expand” and #{t "λαρ̄ώβ", "ləřāb"} “be widened, expanded”. Nowadays this is by far the dominant pattern used in written Alashian and the only one used in speech.
    %p The one exception to this pattern is the imperfect, which has never fully lost the quality of the first vowel. As a result, the first vowel is always lengthened: #{t "λήρ̄εв̄ετ", "lēřevet"} “you (m) were widening” (not **leřřebet), #{t "λούρ̄αβ", "lūřab"} “it (m) was being widened” (not **luřřab).

  = section "C3 = Ř" do
    %p The effects of root-final *Ř are the same as in Scale I. One such root is *mlāř “salty”, which derives the verbs #{t "μαλλήρ̄", "məllēř"} “salt” and #{t "μαλλώρ̄", "məllāř"} “be salted”.
    %p In the present tense of both <i>kəthēb</i> and <i>kəthāb</i> and the imperative of <i>kəthēb</i>, the feminine singular marker *-ī is replaced by *-ēyi, spelled -ηι: #{t "μαλλερ̄ήι", "məlleřēyi"} “salt! (f)” (not **məlleřī), #{t "ιυμαλλαρ̄ήι", "yuməllařēyi"} “it (f) is being salted” (not **yuməllařī).
    %p In addition, the /i/ that immediately precedes #{template "C3"} in the active participle is lowered to /e/: #{t "μύμαλλερ̄", "muməlleř"} “salting” (not **muməlliř).

  = section "C1 = '/H" do
    %p Root-initial *' and *H are prone to dropping, but are not especially problematic. Such roots include *'xīr “be late, last” and *hlāk “behave”#{footnote}, yielding the Scale II verbs #{t "αχχήρ", "'əxxēr"} “delay”, #{t "αχχώρ", "'əxxār"} “be delayed”, and #{t "ηαλλήκ", "həllēk"} “behave”.
    %p These verbs are only irregular when a prefix is present, namely in the present, perfective subjunctive, and deverbatives. In these forms, the *'/H is replaced by /j/: #{t "άιαχχαρ", "'ayəxxar"} “I am delaying” (not **'a'axxar), #{t "в̄ήιαλλεκ", "vēyəllek"} “[that] he/she/they behaved” (not **vēhəllek), #{t "μύιαχχαρ", "muyəxxar"} “being delayed, delayed”.
    %p All other forms are regular.

  = section "C2 = '/H" do
    %p Medial *' and *H suffer from the same problems as medial *Ř: Alashian phonotactics do not allow them to undergo gemination. Thus, just as with medial *Ř, two possible resolutions exist: the older technique, calling for the compensatory lengthening of the previous vowel, and the newer technique, simply ignoring the need for gemination. Using the older technique, the root *k'āb “hurt, be painful” produces the verbs #{t "κωήβ", "kā'ēb"} “hurt, cause pain” and #{t "κουώβ", "kū'āb"} “be hurt”, while using the newer technique, these forms become #{t "καήβ", "kə'ēb"} and #{t "καώβ", "kə'āb"}.
    %p In the imperfect tense, however, compensatory lengthening is required: #{t "κήεв̄ετ", "kē'evet"} “you were hurting” (not **ke''evet), #{t "κηεβού", "kē'ebū"} “they were being hurt” (not **ke''ebū).

  = section "C3 = '" do
    %p Root-final *' behaves quite erratically, but has all of the same irregularities as Scale I verbs. The root *brī' “pure, clear, free” will be used to demonstrate; its Scale II realizations are #{t "βαρρή", "bərrē"} “purify, liberate, pronounce free (of a debt, claim, etc)” and #{t "βαρρώ", "bərrā"} “be purified, pronounced free”.
    %p In the present tense of both <i>kəthēb</i> and <i>kəthāb</i> verbs, the glottal stop drops entirely when word-final and assimilates into the preceding consonant when there is a suffix, causing gemination.
    - alashian = %w(άβαρρα τίβαρρα τιβαρρεί ίβαρρα ιβαρρεί νιβαρρού τιβαρρού τιβαρρού ιβαρρού ιβαρρού)
    - latin = %w('abərra tibərra tibərrī yibərra yibərrī nibərrū tibərrū tibərrū yibərrū yibərrū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Present Tense", :verb => { :ala => "bərrē", :eng => "purify" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The preterite features the same special set of suffixes as seen in Scale I. In the first person singular, the glottal stop drops and the two vowels on either side contract to an unstressed long vowel /aː/. In the first person plural, it assimilates into the following /n/, causing gemination. In the second person masculine forms, the /t/ of the ending becomes an aspirated /tʰ/, while in the feminine forms the /ʃ/ becomes /tʃʰ/. In the third person masculine singular the glottal stop simply drops, while the other third person forms are regular.
    - alashian = %w(βαρρήτ βαρρήττα βαρρήτζζε βαρρή βαρρηώ βαρρηνώ βαρρήττυν βαρρήτζζιν βαρρηού βαρρηού)
    - latin = %w(bərrēt bərētha bərrēčhe bərrē birrē'ā bərrēnnā bərēthun bərēčhin birrē'ū birrē'ū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "bərrē", :eng => "purify" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The imperfect is similarly messy. When word-final (1Sg/3SgM), the glottal stop simply drops. When surrounded on both sides by /e/ (1Pl/2SgM/2SgF), it drops and the two vowels contract to an unstressed /eː/. In the second person plural forms, the suffix becomes aspirated as in the preterite.
    - alashian = %w(βέρρε βέρρητ βέρρης̄ βέρρε βερρεώ βέρρην βέρραττυν βέρρατζζιν βερρεού βερρεού)
    - latin = %w(berre berrēt berrēš berre berre'ā berrēn berrəthun berrəčhin berre'ū berre'ū)
    = render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Imperfect Tense", :verb => { :ala => "bərrē", :eng => "purify" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The glottal stop drops in all forms of the perfective subjunctive:
    - alashian = %w(в̄άβαρρε в̄ετείβαρρε в̄ήβαρρε в̄ενείβαρρε в̄ετείβαρρε в̄ήβαρρε)
    - latin = %w(vabərre vetībərre vēbərre venībərre vetībərre vēbərre)
    = render 'subjunctive_table', :title => "Scale II Perfective Subjunctive", :verb => { :ala => "bərrē", :eng => "purify" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p In the imperative (<i>kəthēb</i> only), the glottal stop is lost in the masculine singular due to being word-final:
    - alashian = %w(βαρρή βαρρεεί βαρρεού βαρρεού)
    - latin = %w(bərrē bərre'ī bərre'ū bərre'ū)
    = render 'imperative_table', :title => "Scale II Imperative", :verb => { :ala => "bərrē", :eng => "purify" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
    %p The deverbatives simply lose the glottal stop, but are otherwise regular:
    - alashian = [ { :name => "Infinitive", :ala => "μαβαρρού", :lat => "mabərrū", :meaning => "purify" },
                   { :name => "Active Part.", :ala => "μύβαρρι", :lat => "mubərri", :meaning => "purifying" } ]

  = section "C3 = H" do
    %p Final *H behaves in a rather unusual manner. In Scale II, #{template "C2"} and #{template "C3"} appear to switch places, so that a root such as *zgāh “crazy, mad” forms the verbs #{t "ζαηήγ", "zəhēg"} “drive mad” and #{t "ζαηώγ", "zəhāg"} “be driven mad” (cf. the <i>katab</i> form #{t "ζαγώ", "zagā"} “be crazy, mad”). More precisely, roots with final *H adopt a biconsonantal-like paradigm outside of Scale I, which in turn undergo internal extension with -h- in Scale II.
    %p The conjugation of #{t "ζαηήγ", "zəhēg"}, therefore, follows the #{template "C2"} = *H pattern, as though the root were actually *zhāg. Just as with true #{template "C2"} = *H verbs, two possible paradigms exist; shown below is the newer, more common system:
    - alashian = { :present     => %w(άζαηαγ τίζαηαγ τιζαηαγεί ίζαηαγ ιζαηαγεί νιζαηαγού τιζαηαγού τιζαηαγού ιζαηαγού),
                   :preterite   => %w(ζαηήγετ ζαηήγ̄τα ζαηήγ̄σ̄ε ζαηήγ ζιηηγώ ζαηηγνώ ζαηήγ̄τυν ζαηήγ̄σ̄ιν ζιηηγού),
                   :imperfect   => %w(ζήηεγ̄ ζήηεγ̄ετ ζήηεγ̄ες̄ ζήηεγ ζηηεγώ ζήηεγ̄εν ζήηεγ̄τυν ζήηεγ̄σ̄ιν ζηηεγού),
                   :subjunctive => %w(в̄άζαηεγ в̄ετείζαηεγ в̄ετείζαηεγ в̄ήζαηεγ в̄ήζαηεγ в̄ενείζαηεγ в̄ετείζαηεγ в̄ετείζαηεγ в̄ήζαηεγ),
                   :imperative  => %w(ζαηήγ ζαηεγεί ζαηεγού),
                   :infinitive  => "μαζαηούγ",
                   :participle  => "μύζαηιγ" }
    - latin = { :present     => %w('azəhag tizəhag tizəhagī yizəhag yizəhagī nizəhagū tizəhagū tizəhagū yizəhagū),
                :preterite   => %w(zəhēget zəhēǧta zəhēǧše zəhēg zihēgā zəhēgnā zəhēǧtun zəhēǧšin zihēgū),
                :imperfect   => %w(zēheǧ zēheǧet zēheǧeš zēheg zēhegā zēheǧen zēheǧtun zēheǧšin zēhegū),
                :subjunctive => %w(vazəheg vetīzəheg vetīzəheg vēzəheg vēzəheg venīzəheg vetīzəheg vetīzəheg vēzəheg),
                :imperative  => %w(zəhēg zəhegī zəhegū),
                :infinitive  => "mazəhūg",
                :participle  => "muzəhig" }
    = render 'full_conjugation_table', :title => "Scale II Conjugation", :verb => { :ala => "zəhēg", :eng => "drive mad" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin

  = section "C1 = Y/W" do
    %p Root-initial *Y and *W are actually completely regular in Scale II. Example roots instead *ybīs “dry”, yielding #{t "ιαββής", "yəbbēs"} “dry” and #{t "ιαββώς", "yəbbās"} “be dried”, and *wsīn “sleep”, yielding #{t "в̄ασσήν", "vəssēn"} “put [a child] to bed, say 'good night'” and #{t "в̄ασσών", "vəssān"} “be put to bed, be told 'good night'”. Roots with initial *W will automatically alternate between /v/ word-initially and /w/ word-internally.

  = section "C3 = Y/W" do
    %p The consonants *Y and *W in #{template "C3"} position will monophthongize or drop entirely when word-final or checked by another consonant. At times they will disappear intervocalically as well. Two such roots are *zmāy “thirsty”, yielding #{t "ζαμμή", "zəmmē"} “make thirsty” and #{t "ζαμμώ", "zəmmā"} “be made thirsty”, and *bdāw “empty, desolate”, yielding #{t "βαδδή", "bəddē"} “empty” and #{t "βαδδώ", "bəddā"} “be emptied”.
    %p In the <i>kəthēb</i> present tense, the word-final sequences *-ay and *-aw collapse into an unstressed *-ē and -ū respectively: #{t "άζαμμη", "'azəmmē"} “I make thirst” (not **'azəmmay), #{t "τίβαδδου", "tibəddū"} “you (m) empty” (not **tibəddaw). Suffixed forms are regular: #{t "νιζαμιού", "nizəmyū"} “we make thirst”, #{t "ιβαδυεί", "yibədwī"} “she empties”.
    %p The <i>kəthēb</i> preterite forms lose the final *Y/W in all cases other than the third person singular feminine and third person plural: #{t "ζαμμήτα", "zəmmēta"} “you (m) made thirst” (not **zəmmēyta), #{t "βιδδηυώ", "biddēwā"} “she emptied”. In the first person singular, contraction takes place: #{t "ζαμμήτ", "zəmmēt"} “I made thirst” (not **zəmmēyet), #{t "βαδδήτ", "bəddēt"} “I emptied” (not **bəddēwet).
    %p In the <i>kəthēb</i> imperfect, the sequences *-ey and *-eye- both collapse into *-ē-, with a stress shift if appropriate: #{t "ζεμμής̄", "zemmēš"} “you (f) were making thirst” (not **zemmeyeš), #{t "ζεμμή", "zemmē"} “he was making thirst” (not **zemmey). The third person singular feminine and third person plural are regular. When #{template "C3"} = *W, the result of *-ew and *-ewe- contraction may be either *-ū- or *-ē- (as in <i>katab</i>), with the latter being more common nowadays: #{t "βεδδούν", "beddūn"} / #{t "βεδδήν", "beddēn"} “we were emptying” (not **beddewen).
    %p In the <i>kəthēb</i> perfective subjunctive, #{template "C3"} simply drops and the vowel immediately beforehand lengthens in compensation, with stress shifting to the last syllable: #{t "в̄αζαμμή", "vazəmmē"} “[that] I made thirst” (not **vazəmmey), #{t "в̄ετειβαδδή", "vetībəddē"} “[that] you (m) counted” (not **vetībəddew).
    %p In the <i>kəthēb</i> imperative, #{template "C3"} drops in the masculine singular and is kept in other forms: #{t "βαδδή", "bəddē"} “empty! (m)” (not **bəddēw), #{t "βαδδευεί", "bəddewī"} “empty! (f)”.
    %p The <i>kəthēb</i> infinitive is formed regularly, except that C<sub>3</sub> is absent. The active participle is similar, except that the short /i/ is lengthened to /iː/ and it declines as though it had the nisba suffix (see adjectives section) in all forms other than the masculine singular.
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        %td
          %table
            %tr
              %th{:colspan => 3} Scale II Deverbatives: <i>zəmmē</i> “make thirst”
            %tr
              %th
              %th Infinitive
              %th Active Part.
            %tr
              %th Masc Sg
              %td{:rowspan => 2}= t("μαζαμμού", "mazəmmū", :linebreak => true)
              %td= t("μυζαμμεί", "muzəmmī", :linebreak => true)
            %tr
              %th Fem Sg
              %td= t("μυζαμμιιώ", "muzəmmiyyā", :linebreak => true)
            %tr
              %th Meaning
              %th make thirst
              %th making thirst
        %td
          %table
            %tr
              %th{:colspan => 3} Scale II Deverbatives: <i>bəddē</i> “empty”
            %tr
              %th
              %th Infinitive
              %th Active Part.
            %tr
              %th Masc Sg
              %td{:rowspan => 2}= t("μαβαδδού", "mabəddū", :linebreak => true)
              %td= t("μυβαδδεί", "mubəddī", :linebreak => true)
            %tr
              %th Fem Sg
              %td= t("μυβαδδιιώ", "mubəddiyyā", :linebreak => true)
            %tr
              %th Meaning
              %th empty
              %th emptying
    %p <i>Kəthāb</i> forms closely mirror <i>kəthēb</i>, with some variation in how monophthongization occurs.
    %p In the <i>kəthāb</i> present tense, #{template "C3"} drops when word-final; otherwise the forms are regular: #{t "υζαμμώ", "'uzəmmā"} “I am made thirsty” (not **'uzəmmāy), #{t "ιυβαδδαυού", "yubəddawū"} “they are emptied”.
    %p In the <i>kəthāb</i> preterite, #{template "C3"} is lost when word-final or checked: #{t "ζαμμώτα", "zəmmāta"} “you (m) were made thirsty” (not **zəmmāyta). In the first person singular, #{template "C3"} is also lost and contraction takes place: #{t "βαδδώτ", "bəddāt"} “I was emptied” (not **bəddāwet).
    %p The sequences *-ay/*-aya- and *-aw/*-awa- in the <i>kəthāb</i> imperfect collapse into *-ā- and *-ā-/*-ū- respectively: #{t "ζυμμώ", "zummā"} “I was being made thirsty” (not **zummay), #{t "βυδδώτυν", "buddātun"} / #{t "βυδδούτυν", "buddūtun"} “you all (m) were being emptied” (not **buddawtun). For #{template "C3"} = *W roots, the *-ā- realization is more common nowadays.
    %p In the <i>kəthāb</i> perfective subjunctive, #{template "C3"} drops and the preceding vowel is lengthened in compensation.
    %p #{template "C3"} drops in the <i>kəthāb</i> infinitive: #{t "μαζαμμώ", "mazəmmā"} “be made thirsty” (not **mazəmmāy), #{t "μαβαδδώ", "mabəddā"} “be emptied” (not **mabəddāw). The participle undergoes monothongization depending on #{template "C3"}: #{t "μυζαμμή", "muzəmmē"} “being made thirsty” (not **muzəmmay), #{t "μυβαδδού", "mubəddū"} “being emptied” (not **mubəddaw).

  = section "C1/C2/C3 = N" do
    %p Roots with *N—including *nmīs “envy” (#{t "ναμμής", "nəmmēs"} “make envious” and #{t "ναμμώς", "nəmmās"} “be made envious”), *snād “arm” (#{t "σαννήδ", "sənnēd"} “lean” and #{t "σαννώδ", "sənnād"} “be leaned”), and *lbīn “white” (#{t "λαββήν", "ləbbēn"} “whiten” and #{t "λαββών", "ləbbān"} “be whitened”—tend to undergo assimilation in Alashian, but in Scale II at least they are quite regular. In fact, only #{template "C3"} = N roots are irregular.
    %p Root-final *N is only irregular in the two past tenses, as the *N assimilates into the following consonant in many forms. The following tables show the <i>kəthēb</i> and <i>kəthāb</i> forms of *lbīn:
    %table.invisible
      %tr
        - alashian = %w(λαββήνετ λαββήττα λαββήτζζε λαββήν λιββηνώ λαββηννώ λαββήττυν λαββήτζζιν λιββηνού λιββηνού)
        - latin = %w(ləbbēnet ləbbētha ləbbēčhe ləbbēn libbēnā ləbbēnnā ləbbēthun ləbbēčhin libbēnū libbēnū)
        %td= render 'verb_table', :title => "Scale II Preterite Tense", :verb => { :ala => "ləbbēn", :eng => "whiten" }, :alashian => alashian, :latin => latin
